                        <span class="s2">&quot;*&quot;</span><span class="o">:</span> <span class="s2">&quot;{{Infobox comics creator\n&lt;!-- | name          = --&gt;\n| image         = File:Creig Flessel.jpg\n| imagesize     = 200\n| caption       = Creig Flessel\n| birth_name    = Creig Valentine Flessel\n| birth_date    = February 2, 1912\n| birth_place      = [[Huntington, New York|Huntington]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2008|7|17|1912|2|2}}\n| death_place   = [[Mill Valley]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| area          = Penciller\n| alias         =\n| signature     =\n| notable works = [[Sandman (Wesley Dodds)|Sandman]]&lt;br&gt;[[Shining Knight]]\n| awards        =\n}}\n&#39;&#39;&#39;Creig Valentine Flessel&#39;&#39;&#39; (February 2, 1912 &amp;ndash; July 17, 2008)&lt;ref name=ssdi&gt;[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JTFV-LM5 Creig Valentine Flessel] at the United States [[Social Security Death Index]] via [[FamilySearch.org]]. Retrieved on November 5, 2015. Also [http://www.genealogybank.com/gbnk/ssdi/doc/ssdi/v1:1251023DA578D988 Creig Valentine Flessel] at the United States Social Security Death Index via GenealogyBank.com. Retrieved February 6, 2013.&lt;/ref&gt; was an [[United States|American]] [[comic book artist]] and an [[illustrator]] and [[cartoonist]] for magazines ranging from &#39;&#39;[[Boys&#39; Life]]&#39;&#39; to &#39;&#39;[[Playboy]]&#39;&#39;. One of the earliest comic book illustrators, he was a 2006 nominee for induction into the comics industry&#39;s [[List of Eisner Award winners#The Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame|Will Eisner Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and career===\nThe son of Frank John Flessel, a [[blacksmith]], and his wife Ida Hawkins Bunce, Flessel was born in [[Huntington, New York|Huntington]], [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]].&lt;ref name=surnames&gt;{{cite web | url = http://longislandsurnames.com/genealogy/familygroup.php?familyID=F1759&amp;tree=Bunce | title = Family: Creig Valentine Flessel/Marie G Marino (F1759) | publisher = Long Island Surnames | accessdate = February 6, 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name = tcjinterview&gt;{{cite news | url = http://www.tcj.com/the-creig-flessel-interview/ | title = The Creig Flessel Interview | work = [[The Comics Journal]] | date = August 22, 2001 | accessdate = February 6, 2013 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110907105644/http://www.tcj.com/the-creig-flessel-interview/ | archivedate = September 7, 2011 | url-status = live | quote = My older brother was very mechanical. ... I have two older sisters.}}&lt;/ref&gt; He was the youngest of two boys and two girls,&lt;ref name = tcjinterview /&gt; with siblings Frank Bunce Flessel, Laura E. Flessel, and Elizabeth Flessel.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url = http://longislandsurnames.com/genealogy/getperson.php?personID=I3429&amp;tree=Bunce | title = Frank John Flessel | publisher = Long Island Surnames | accessdate = February 6, 2013 | archivedate = January 8, 2016 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160108033855/http://longislandsurnames.com/getperson.php?personID=I3429&amp;tree=Bunce | url-status = dead }}&lt;/ref&gt; Flessel graduated high school in 1930 then attended Grand Central Art School, at [[Grand Central Terminal]] in [[Manhattan]], working as a door monitor in exchange for art lessons from instructors including the painter [[Harvey Dunn]].&lt;ref name = tcjinterview /&gt; He studied there for two years, with cartoonist [[Charles Addams]] a classmate and casual acquaintance.&lt;ref name = tcjinterview /&gt;&lt;ref name=ncs&gt;{{cite web | url = http://www.reuben.org/ncs/members/bios/Flessel.jpg | title = Creig Flessel 1912- | publisher =  [[National Cartoonists Society]] | accessdate =  2008-07-21 | archivedate = June 4, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120604062424/http://www.reuben.org/ncs/members/bios/Flessel.jpg | url-status = live}}&lt;/ref&gt; Afterward, he worked one summer as a gardener on [[William K. Vanderbilt]]\u2019s estate, earning $25 a week.&lt;ref name = tcjinterview /&gt;\n\nFlessel began drawing for the [[pulp magazine]]s of the time, including [[Street &amp; Smith]]&#39;s &#39;&#39;[[The Shadow]]&#39;&#39;. \&quot;They would give you a copy of a story and the space. Double spread would be $15; single would be seven, sometimes ten,\&quot; Flessel recalled in 2001.&lt;ref name= tcj2&gt;\&quot;The Creig Flessel Interview\&quot; (2001), p. [http://www.tcj.com/the-creig-flessel-interview/2/ 2].  [https://www.webcitation.org/6EE3pH7RR?url=http://www.tcj.com/the-creig-flessel-interview/2/ Archived] from the original on February 6, 2013.&lt;/ref&gt; He broke into comics after answering an ad in &#39;&#39;[[The New York Times]]&#39;&#39; by Major [[Major Malcolm Wheeler-Nicholson]],&lt;ref name= tcj2 /&gt; whose National Allied Publications would eventually become [[DC Comics]], and began freelancing there. His first known work for the publisher appeared in &#39;&#39;[[More Fun Comics]]&#39;&#39; #10 ([[cover-date]]d May 1936), [[penciler|penciling]] and [[inker|inking]] the two-page [[sword-and-sorcery]] feature \&quot;Don Drake\&quot; and the two-page humor strip \&quot;Fishy Frolics\&quot;.&lt;ref name=gcd&gt;[http://www.comics.org/credit/name/Creig%20Flessel/sort/chrono/ Creig Flessel] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]&lt;/ref&gt; Flessel recalled,\n{{quote|I don\u2019t think they were looking for any pedigree or \&quot;Would you do this?\&quot; More like, \&quot;You\u2019re a live body. What do you want to do? Take this and do it, then.\&quot; I realized they were desperate so I had to go out and buy a drawing table. They had just one table that they were doing all of the mechanical work on. So I got a table and managed to find a chair and sat down and they said, \&quot;Here. Do this.\&quot; I think I did a couple of center spreads for &#39;&#39;[[More Fun Comics|More Fun]]&#39;&#39;. I did [the feature] \&quot;Fishy Frolics\&quot;, I did an \&quot;Acorn and Andy\&quot; double-spread. Little nonsense cartoons.&lt;ref name= tcj2 /&gt;}}\n[[Image:Detective Comics 7.jpg|thumb|left|Creig Flessel&#39;s cover for &#39;&#39;Detective Comics&#39;&#39; #7 (Sept.1937)]]\n\nIn 1936, Flessel applied for a position with the [[advertising agency]] Johnstone and Cushing, and the firm, feeling he needed more experience, recommended him as an assistant to cartoonist [[John H. Striebel]] on the [[newspaper]] [[comic strip]] &#39;&#39;[[Dixie Dugan]]&#39;&#39;. He worked for Striebel \&quot;[h]alf a day for a year, while I was doing pulps and of course keeping my contact with Johnstone and Cushing, maybe picking up a job,\&quot; while also continuing to work for Wheeler-Nicholson.&lt;ref name= tcj2 /&gt; Flessel also assisted Streibel with advertising art featuring the humorous [[radio program]] characters &#39;&#39;[[Vic and Sade]]&#39;&#39;, who appeared in [[Farina (food)|Farina Wheat]] cereal print ads. Flessel next found work with the major [[advertising agency]] Johnstone and Cushing, illustrating ads for [[Nestle]] [[Chocolate-chip cookie|Toll House cookies]]&lt;!--Toll House capped -- name of restaurant where this type of cookie originated--&gt;, [[General Foods]], [[Raisin Bran]], [[Eveready Battery Company|Eveready]] batteries, the [[Nehi]] Beverage Company&#39;s [[R.C. Cola]] (with the characters R.C. and Quickie) and other brands and products.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nOn November 20, 1937, Flessel and Marie G. Marino were married in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]].\n\n===Golden Age of comic books===\nConcentrating his attention on the fledgling comics medium, Flessel drew the covers of many of the first [[American comic books]], including the pre-[[Batman]] &#39;&#39;[[Detective Comics]]&#39;&#39; #2-19 (April 1937 - Sept. 1938). He both wrote and drew the two-page \&quot;Steve Conrad, Adventurer\&quot;, premiering in &#39;&#39;New Comics&#39;&#39; #5 (June 1936); the two-page [[sports]] feature \&quot;Pep Morgan\&quot;, premiering &#39;&#39;More Fun&#39;&#39; #12 (Aug. 1936); \&quot;Bret Lawton\&quot; and \&quot;Speed Saunders\&quot; (the latter with writer E. C. Stoner and later [[Gardner Fox]]), both premiering in &#39;&#39;Detective Comics&#39;&#39; #1; \&quot;Bradley Boys\&quot;, premiering in &#39;&#39;More Fun&#39;&#39; #13; \&quot;Hanko the Cowhand\&quot;, premiering in \&quot;More Fun\&quot; #25 (Oct. 1937); \&quot;Buzz Brown\&quot;, premiering in &#39;&#39;More Fun&#39;&#39; #30 (March 1938); and at least drew and possibly wrote \&quot;Red Coat Patrol\&quot; also known as \&quot;Sgt. O&#39;Malley\&quot;, premiering in \&quot;More Fun\&quot; #39 (Jan. 1939).  As writer-artist, Flessel created the DC character the [[Shining Knight]], in &#39;&#39;Adventure Comics&#39;&#39; #66 (Sept. 1941).&lt;ref name=gcd /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.toonopedia.com/shknight.htm The Shining Knight] at [[Don Markstein&#39;s Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/62hb1aIXs?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/shknight.htm Archived] from the original on October 25, 2011.&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nFlessel, who drew many early adventures of the Golden Age [[Sandman (Wesley Dodds)|Sandman]] and is closely associated with that character, has sometimes been credited as the character&#39;s co-creator. While Flessel drew the &#39;&#39;Sandman&#39;&#39; cover of &#39;&#39;[[Adventure Comics]]&#39;&#39; #40, generally considered the character&#39;s first appearance,&lt;ref&gt;The Sandman appeared in both &#39;&#39;[[Adventure Comics]]&#39;&#39; #40 (July 1939) and in DC Comics&#39; 1939 &#39;&#39;[[1939 New York World&#39;s Fair|New York World&#39;s Fair]] Comics&#39;&#39;, &#39;&#39;Omnibus&#39;&#39;, which historians believe may have appeared on newsstands one to two weeks earlier, though the &#39;&#39;Adventure Comics&#39;&#39; story is believed to have been written and drawn first. Both appearances are by writer [[Gardner Fox]] and artist [[Bert Christman]].&lt;/ref&gt; the character was created by writer [[Gardner Fox]] and artist [[Bert Christman]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.toonopedia.com/articles/sandman1.htm Sandman]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} at Don Markstein&#39;s Toonopedia. [https://www.webcitation.org/62haySUQN?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sandman1.htm Archived] from the original on October 25, 2011.&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nWhen DC Comics editor [[Vin Sullivan]] left the company in 1940 to work for [[Columbia Comics]], Flessel, Fox and others freelanced for his &#39;&#39;Big Shot Comics&#39;&#39;. In 1943, when Sullivan formed his own comic book publishing company, [[Magazine Enterprises]], Flessel signed on as associate editor. Among its other publications, the firm produced at least three issues of the highly violent, wartime [[propaganda]] comic &#39;&#39;The United States Marines&#39;&#39;, which presented \&quot;Authentic [[U.S. Marine Corps]] Picture Stories\&quot; as well as graphic government photographs of such subjects as burned and bayoneted Japanese soldiers.\n[[Image:AlterEgo45.jpg|thumb|left|&#39;&#39;Alter Ego&#39;&#39; #45 (Feb. 2005): New Sandman cover art by then 93-year-old Flessel]]\nFlessel drew illustrations for several issues of the [[pulp magazine]] &#39;&#39;Clues Detective Stories&#39;&#39; in 1939 and 1940.  During the late 1950s he also provided uncredited artwork for [[Al Capp]]&#39;s &#39;&#39;[[Li&#39;l Abner]]&#39;&#39; comic strip.&lt;ref name=tcr&gt;{{cite web\n |last=Spurgeon \n |first=Tom \n |authorlink=Tom Spurgeon \n |title=Creig Flessel, 1912\u20132008 \n |work=The Comics Reporter \n |date=July 21, 2008 \n |url=http://www.comicsreporter.com/index.php/creig_flessel_1912_2008/ \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5syHFiJIk?url=http://www.comicsreporter.com/index.php/creig_flessel_1912_2008/ \n |archivedate=September 24, 2010\n |accessdate=July 21, 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}.&lt;/ref&gt;\n\n===Later life and career===\nFlessel continued to draw comics, often uncredited, through the 1950s, including [[Superboy]] stories in both that character&#39;s namesake title and in &#39;&#39;Adventure Comics&#39;&#39;; and anthological [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] and suspense tales in [[American Comics Group]] (AGC&#39;s) &#39;&#39;Adventures into the Unknown&#39;&#39;. Flessel&#39;s final regular comic-book work was penciling and inking the 6{{fraction|2|3}}-page story \&quot;The Flying Girl of Smallville\&quot; in &#39;&#39;Superboy&#39;&#39; #72 (April 1959). He returned in the 1970s to do occasional inking for writer-penciler [[Joe Simon]], as on &#39;&#39;[[Prez (DC Comics)|Prez]]&#39;&#39; #4 (March 1973).&lt;ref name=gcd /&gt;\n[[Image:DavidCrane,6-10-61.jpg|thumb|270px|Creig Flessel&#39;s &#39;&#39;David Crane&#39;&#39; (June 10, 1961). The titular minister is not depicted in this particular slice of small-town life.]]\nBeginning in 1960, Flessel drew a [[Hall Syndicate]] comic strip about a young [[minister of religion|minister]], &#39;&#39;David Crane&#39;&#39;, created by [[Ed Dodd]] in 1956 and originally produced by artist [[Win Mortimer]] and writer Hart Spence.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,862020,00.html| title=Religion: Comic Cleric| work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]| date=March 12, 1956| accessdate=January 8, 2016| archivedate=April 18, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418170001/http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C862020%2C00.html| url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 1993, Flessel donated the original art for 2,677 strips to the [[Ohio State University]] Cartoon, Graphic and Photographic Arts Research Library. After &#39;&#39;David Crane&#39;&#39; ceased publication in 1971, Flessel unsuccessfully attempted several other strips, including &#39;&#39;Cy Poppins&#39;&#39;, about the owner of a country store; &#39;&#39;Willie Wildwood&#39;&#39;, an environmentally aware strip; and &#39;&#39;The Other Foot.&#39;&#39;&lt;ref name=tcr /&gt;\n\nLike his friend [[Jack Cole (artist)|Jack Cole]], creator of &#39;&#39;[[Plastic Man]]&#39;&#39;, Flessel also regularly contributed cartoons to &#39;&#39;Playboy&#39;&#39; magazine, including a series titled \&quot;The Adventures of Baron Furstinbed\&quot;. Many of these cartoons were reprinted in the one-shot &#39;&#39;Sex and Other Late Night Laughs&#39;&#39; (1990), collecting the work of 26 &#39;&#39;Playboy&#39;&#39; cartoonists.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.oddball-comics.com/article.php?story=2008-08-04|authorlink=Scott Shaw | last=Shaw | first = Scott|title=&#39;&#39;Refreshment Through the Ages&#39;&#39;|date = August 3, 2008 |publisher= Oddball Comics| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120321044659/http://www.oddball-comics.com/article.php?story=2008-08-04 | archivedate=March 21, 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nIn 2000, Flessel and his wife Marie moved from the East Coast to [[Mill Valley, California|Mill Valley]], [[California]], where he continued to create art for local events and talent shows.&lt;ref name=evanier /&gt; Their son, Peter Flessel, is an [[environmental engineer]], and their daughter, Eugenie Fernandes, is a book illustrator and author in Ontario.&lt;ref name=ncs /&gt;&lt;ref name=evanier /&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url =http://www.annickpress.com/authors/fernandes-e.asp?author=342 | publisher = Annick Press | title = Eugenie Fernandes | accessdate = February 6, 2013 | archivedate = July 1, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120701124500/http://www.annickpress.com/authors/fernandes-e.asp?author=342 | url-status = live}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nIn his final years, Flessel was rediscovered by comic fandom and was the recipient of many honors. He was a guest of honor at the [[fan convention]] Wondercon in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[California]], in February 2005, speaking on the Golden/Silver Age Panel. Flessel is also mentioned in [[Michael Chabon]]&#39;s 2000 novel &#39;&#39;[[The Amazing Adventures of Kavalier &amp; Clay]]&#39;&#39; (though his name is misspelled \&quot;Craig\&quot; in early editions).&lt;ref&gt;On page 144 of the first printing, the quote reads \&quot;These guys aren&#39;t trying to draw bad, Joe. Some of what they do is okay. There&#39;s a guy, Craig Flessel, he&#39;s really pretty good. Try to keep an open mind.\&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;\n\nFlessel suffered a [[stroke]]&lt;ref name=evanier&gt;{{cite web|authorlink=Mark Evanier |last=Evanier |first=Mark |url=http://www.newsfromme.com/archives/2008_07_19.html |title=Creig Flessel, R.I.P. |publisher=P.O.V. Online |date=July 19, 2008 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archivedate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61CxMfdfh?url=http://www.newsfromme.com/archives/2008_07_19.html |url-status=live }}&lt;/ref&gt; &lt;!--on July 11, 2008 that left him paralyzed on his right side. He--&gt; and shortly afterward died at his home in [[Mill Valley]], [[California]], on July 17, 2008.&lt;ref name=ssdi /&gt;&lt;ref name=tcr /&gt;\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*1991 [[Comic-Con International]] [[Inkpot Award]]\n*1992 [[National Cartoonists Society]] Silver T-Square Extraordinary Service Award{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n*2006 nominee for induction, [[List of Eisner Award winners#The Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame|Will Eisner Hall of Fame]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url = http://www.comic-con.org/cci/cci_eisners06nom.shtml | title = 2006 Eisner Award Nominations | publisher = [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] | archivedate = May 15, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120515040204/http://www.comic-con.org/cci/cci_eisners06nom.shtml}}&lt;/ref&gt;\n*2007 &#39;&#39;The Sparky Award&#39;&#39; given by Jeannie Schulz and the Cartoon Art Museum, San Francisco{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n==Books==\n*&#39;&#39;Along the Shore&#39;&#39; by Elizabeth F. Weidner, illustrated by Creig Flessel (Behrman House, 1985) {{ISBN|0-682-40239-7}}\n*&#39;&#39;Draw 50 People&#39;&#39; by Lee J. Ames with Creig Flessel (Doubleday, 1993; Sagebrush reissue, 1994) {{ISBN|0-613-51071-2}} (reissue)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | 2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external links |date = February 2013}}\n*[http://www.lambiek.net/artists/f/flessel_creig.htm Creig Flessel] at the [[Lambiek Comiclopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/62XOINyiQ?url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/f/flessel_creig.htm Archived] October 18, 2011.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070105044322/http://www.dcindexes.com/database/creator-details.php?creatorid=158 Creig Flessel] at Mike&#39;s Amazing World of DC Comics database\n*[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/fmi/c66.htm#A2955 Creig Flessel] at The FictionMags Index. [https://www.webcitation.org/5to1YRQxb?url=http://www.philsp.com/homeville/fmi/c66.htm WebCitation archive].\n*[http://www.bpib.com/comicsproj/biogF1.html Creig Flessel entry], The Comic Strip Project, \&quot;Who&#39;s Who of Comic Strip Producers\&quot;, F-Part 1. [https://www.webcitation.org/5qyYbgF91?url=http://www.bpib.com/comicsproj/ WebCitation archive]. &lt;!--in case it goes away, as the previous archive link did, here&#39;s a [https://www.webcitation.org/5syITnI9D?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20060506042858/hometown.aol.com/comicsproj/creditsAD.html WebCitation archive of original AOL Hometown site].--&gt;\n*Interview with Creig Flessel, &#39;&#39;The Comics Journal&#39;&#39; #244 (Aug. 2002) pp.&amp;nbsp;54\u201375. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429235327/http://www.tcj.com/245/i_flessel.html |date=April 29, 2008 |title=additional interview material place online }}. Retrieved October 28, 2010. [http://www.tcj.com/245/i_flessel.html Original site]. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123160353/http://www.tcj.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=866&amp;Itemid=48 |date=January 23, 2009 |title=page 1 only }}, \&quot;The Creig Flessel Interview\&quot;, 27 July 2008\n*\&quot;Mr. Sandman: Creig Flessel, Golden Age Legend\&quot;, by Charlie Roberts, &#39;&#39;Comic Book Marketplace&#39;&#39; #15 (July 1992) pp.&amp;nbsp;28\u201333\n**\&quot;Flessel on Flessel\&quot;, pp.&amp;nbsp;36\u201339\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/5syI6jYEa?url=http://www.theredwoods.org/redwoodsV3.pdf &#39;&#39;The Redwoods Review&#39;&#39; (Fall 2004): \&quot;The Amazing Adventures of...Creig Flessel!\&quot;] (community newspaper; link opens PDF). [https://www.webcitation.org/5syI6jYEa?url=http://www.theredwoods.org/redwoodsV3.pdf WebCitation archive].\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060622000747/http://www.berndttoastgang.com/News.html |date=June 22, 2006 |title=NCS Long Island Chapter \&quot;The Berndt Toast Gang\&quot; News }} (newsletter); includes handwritten Flessel letter. [http://www.berndttoastgang.com/News.html Original page].\n\n==Further reading==\n*&#39;&#39;Comic-Book Superstars&#39;&#39;, by Don &amp; Maggie Thompson (Krause Publications, Iola, Wis., 1993) Entry, pp.&amp;nbsp;70\u201371\n*&#39;&#39;The Great Comic Book Artists, Vol. 2&#39;&#39;, by Ron Goulart (St. Martin&#39;s Press, New York, 1989) Entry pp.&amp;nbsp;36\u201337\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flessel, Creig}}\n[[Category:American comics artists]]\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alfred University alumni]]\n[[Category:Golden Age comics creators]]&quot;</span>
